         "id": "introduction_section",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen studying the addition operation, we learn that the commutative property exists for numbers. This means that the result remains the same regardless of the order in which we add them",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team, Adding the same numbers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Inheritance of Properties</b><br /><br />Addition is commutative.<br /><br />Multiplication is a sequence of additions.<br /><br />Given these two premises, can we expect multiplication to also preserve its result when the numbers are inverted?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            }
         ]
      },
      {
          "id" : "square_section",
          "text" : [ 
            { "text" : "### Equal Numbers\n\nLet us begin by studying equal numbers. For this, we will use the same altar mentioned in the previous text",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team, Adding the same numbers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
              ],
              "isTable" : false,
              "imgdesc" : "",
              "latex" : null,
              "date_time" : null,
              "format" : "markdown",
              "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htSlides\"></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\">Slide 1: Images of Altar Q at the archaeological site of Copán, Honduras. Photo taken during a visit on <htdate0>.<br />The names of the kings (<i>ajawob</i>) are detailed in the work of Anastasia Hutnick (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('85c2d88c-6ad8-4858-95f8-0f157c49bf07'); return false;\">Hutnick, Anastasia, <htdate1>, pp. 18, 35 - 67.</a>).<br />The slide's source code was inspired by a template from (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('cf7adc72-d340-412e-8d48-953ac64cb670'); return false;\">W3Schools</a>).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "4",
                     "day": "26"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2020",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "The altar is shaped like a big box, with inscriptions on top and sculpted human figures on its sides.",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "On Altar Q in Copán, we can observe four *ajawob* (kings) on each side. Thus, regardless of order, we will always multiply 4 by 4.\n\nTo make this operation clearer, we will represent it using squares, each with a side length of one unit",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"center_notation\"><svg width=\"230\" height=\"230\"> <rect x=\"30\" y=\"0\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" style=\"fill:rgb(255,255,255);stroke-width:4;stroke:rgb(0,0,0)\" /> <rect x=\"30\" y=\"50\" width=\"200\" height=\"1\" style=\"fill:rgb(255,255,255);stroke-width:4;stroke:rgb(0,0,0)\" /> <rect x=\"30\" y=\"100\" width=\"200\" height=\"1\" style=\"fill:rgb(255,255,255);stroke-width:4;stroke:rgb(0,0,0)\" /> <rect x=\"30\" y=\"150\" width=\"200\" height=\"1\" style=\"fill:rgb(255,255,255);stroke-width:4;stroke:rgb(0,0,0)\" />            <rect x=\"80\" y=\"0\" width=\"1\" height=\"200\" style=\"fill:rgb(255,255,255);stroke-width:4;stroke:rgb(0,0,0)\" /> <rect x=\"130\" y=\"0\" width=\"1\" height=\"200\" style=\"fill:rgb(255,255,255);stroke-width:4;stroke:rgb(0,0,0)\" /> <rect x=\"180\" y=\"0\" width=\"1\" height=\"200\" style=\"fill:rgb(255,255,255);stroke-width:4;stroke:rgb(0,0,0)\" /> <text x=\"50\" y=\"222\">1</text> <text x=\"100\" y=\"222\">2</text> <text x=\"150\" y=\"222\">3</text> <text x=\"200\" y=\"222\">4</text>        <text x=\"5\" y=\"30\">4</text> <text x=\"5\" y=\"80\">3</text> <text x=\"5\" y=\"130\">2</text> <text x=\"5\" y=\"180\">1</text>     </svg></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 1: Squares representing la multiplication of 4 by 4.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "A larger square composed of sixteen smaller squares. On the left side, the squares are numbered from 1 to 4 (bottom to top). On the bottom side, the squares are numbered from 1 to 4 (left to right).",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "We use squares to demonstrate multiplication for a specific reason. In addition to the visual representation in Chart 1, we call the result of multiplying a number by itself a \"square\"",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "c0c1967a-f27a-4191-82f1-c5e44c44a297",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "date_time": null
                  }
